`,r.jsx(e.h1,{children:"End-to-End Testing"}),`
`,r.jsx(e.p,{children:"End-to-end tests are a step above unit tests, both in terms of complexity and what they test. They focus primarily on the flow of the application, making sure that a user's journey through the application has the expected outcomes. These tests can generally be categorized as:"}),`
`,r.jsxs(e.ul,{children:[`
`,r.jsxs(e.li,{children:[r.jsx(e.strong,{children:"Acceptance Tests"}),": verify that various features and flows meet the customer expectations."]}),`
`,r.jsxs(e.li,{children:[r.jsx(e.strong,{children:"Regression Tests"}),": verify that existing functionality is not broken when new features are added."]}),`
`]}),`
`,r.jsx(e.p,{children:"They should cover user stories that span multiple components and views, such as signing up for an account, logging in and out of the application, updating a profile, etc. These tests are not concerned with the underlying state or implementation of the application - just the end results."}),`
`,r.jsx(e.p,{children:"End-to-end tests usually run in a browser against a live system (in the case of web, using a test runner that automates the browser). Automated E2E tests can take a long time to run because of the different pieces involved and the scope of the tests. You should try to optimize your testing pipeline to run tests in parallel to finish faster."}),`
`,r.jsx(e.p,{children:"Functional tests alone will not give you enough test coverage to avoid regressions. Unit tests aim to provide code coverage depth, while functional tests provide coverage over the breadth of user test scenarios."}),`
`,r.jsx(e.h2,{children:"How to Write"}),`
`,r.jsx(e.p,{children:"End-to-end tests rely on the ability to find elements on the screen and interact with them in an automated way. This means that you need a reliable mechanism for selecting elements. Depending on your testing framework, there are different ways to select elements, including:"}),`
`,r.jsxs(e.ul,{children:[`
`,r.jsxs(e.li,{children:[r.jsx(e.strong,{children:"CSS Selectors"}),": Find elements by using CSS classes or rules (e.g., ",r.jsx(e.code,{children:".your-class-name"}),")"]}),`
`,r.jsxs(e.li,{children:[r.jsx(e.strong,{children:"Element Selectors"}),": Find elements inside the elements (e.g., ",r.jsx(e.code,{children:"#\\@\\@blui-drawerlayout-content > div > header > div > button"}),")"]}),`
